  🔠 functions.OpenWebPage:5 | Return {'content': '## Summary\n\nThis article details recent advancements in solid-state battery (SSB) technology for electric vehicles, highlighting key industry partnerships and prototype testing. It reports on significant progress from Mercedes-Benz, BMW, Stellantis, Hyundai, Toyota, and Nissan, focusing on improved energy density, charging times, and range. The timeline for commercial production is set for the latter half of the 2020s.\n\n## Key Points\n\n1.  **Mercedes-Benz achieved a major milestone by integrating a lithium-metal SSB into a production EQS platform for road testing.** The prototype demonstrated a 25% longer driving range (~620 miles) compared to a standard EQS (~500 miles). (Source: https://carbuzz.com/the-latest-solid-state-battery-developments/#From-The-Lab-To-The-Real-World)\n2.  **BMW is testing sulfide-based solid electrolytes in an i7 test vehicle** in partnership with Solid Power, focusing on investigating cell expansion and temperature control. (Source: https://carbuzz.com/the-latest-solid-state-battery-developments/#From-The-Lab-To-The-Real-World)\n3.  **Stellantis, partnering with Factorial Energy, validated SSBs with an energy density of 375 Wh/kg.** Their batteries promise a charge from 15% to over 90% in 18 minutes at room temperature and can operate in temperatures from -22°F to 113°F. (Source: https://carbuzz.com/the-latest-solid-state-battery-developments/#Refining-The-Technology)\n4.  **Hyundai filed a patent for a simplified SSB design using a copper anode** with a protective coating to prevent corrosion, aiming to reduce production costs. The proposed design has six distinct layers. (Source: https://carbuzz.com/the-latest-solid-state-battery-developments/#Refining-The-Technology)\n5.  **Toyota aims for mass production of SSBs by 2027**, targeting a 20% increase in cruising range and charging times of 10 minutes or less for its first iteration. (Source: https://carbuzz.com/the-latest-solid-state-battery-developments/#By-The-End-Of-The-2020s)\n6.  **Nissan is on track to introduce SSBs by the end of the decade, with 2028 as a target date.** (Source: https://carbuzz.com/the-latest-solid-state-battery-developments/#By-The-End-Of-The-2020s)\n\n## Technical Details\n\n*   **Core Technology:** Solid-state batteries replace the liquid or gel electrolyte in lithium-ion batteries with a solid electrolyte, which can be made from materials like glass, ceramic, or sulfide-based compounds.\n*   **Stellantis Battery Specs:**\n    *   Energy Density: 375 Wh/kg.\n    *   Charging: 15% to >90% in ~18 minutes at room temperature.\n    *   Operating Temperature Range: -22°F to 113°F.\n*   **Hyundai Patent Design:** Proposes a six-layer structure: copper anode collector, protective coating, additional anode layer, solid electrolyte layer, cathode layer, and current collector layer.\n\n## References & Citations\n\n- Source Article: https://carbuzz.com/the-latest-solid-state-battery-developments/\n- Mercedes-Benz EQS Prototype Details: https://carbuzz.com/the-latest-solid-state-battery-developments/#From-The-Lab-To-The-Real-World\n- BMW i7 Testing Details: https://carbuzz.com/the-latest-solid-state-battery-developments/#From-The-Lab-To-The-Real-World\n- Stellantis & Factorial Energy Specifications: https://carbuzz.com/the-latest-solid-state-battery-developments/#Refining-The-Technology\n- Hyundai Patent Information: https://carbuzz.com/the-latest-solid-state-battery-developments/#Refining-The-Technology\n- Toyota Production Timeline: https://carbuzz.com/the-latest-solid-state-battery-developments/#By-The-End-Of-The-2020s\n- Nissan Production Timeline: https://carbuzz.com/the-latest-solid-state-battery-developments/#By-The-End-Of-The-2020s', 'links_on_page': ['https://carbuzz.com/', 'https://carbuzz.com/cars/', 'https://carbuzz.com/marketplace/', 'https://carbuzz.com/news/', 'https://carbuzz.com/features/', 'https://carbuzz.com/marketplace/', 'https://carbuzz.com/best-cars-of-the