     ## 2. Big Companies Involved
     
     ### Battery Manufacturers (Top Players)
     
     #### **Toyota** 🇯🇵
     - **Status:** Pioneer with most patents globally
     - **Target:** Mass production 2027-2028
     - **Technology:** Sulfide-based solid electrolyte
     - **Performance Claims:** 10-minute charging, 20-50% range increase
     - **Investment:** $13.5 billion for EV battery technology by 2030
     
     #### **CATL** 🇨🇳
     - **Status:** World's largest battery manufacturer
     - **Technology:** "Condensed state" battery (hybrid approach)
     - **Energy Density:** 500 Wh/kg achieved in prototypes
     - **Timeline:** Small-scale production by 2027
     
     #### **Samsung SDI** 🇰🇷
     - **Status:** Completed "S-Line" pilot line in 2023
     - **Target:** Mass production 2027
     - **Roadmap:** 900 Wh/L solid-state batteries, cobalt-free designs
     
     #### **LG Energy Solution** 🇰🇷
     - **Investment:** $819M R&D in 2023
     - **Target:** Mass production 2030
     - **Approach:** Future Technology Center focusing on solid-state and lithium-metal
     
     #### **BYD** 🇨🇳
     - **Current:** Blade Battery (LFP) with Cell-to-Pack design
     - **Target:** 500 Wh/kg solid-state, pilot production from 2027
     - **Innovation:** Passed nail penetration, crushing, 300°C heat tests
     
     #### **Factorial Energy** 🇺🇸
     - **Status:** Closest to commercialization among Western players
     - **Partnerships:** Mercedes-Benz, Stellantis, Hyundai
     - **Validation:** 106 Ah cells tested in Mercedes EQS (745+ miles)
     - **Energy Density:** 375 Wh/kg (Stellantis validated)
     - **IPO:** Going public via SPAC merger (Cartesian Growth Corp III) in mid-2026
     
     #### **Solid Power** 🇺🇸
     - **Technology:** Sulfide-based solid electrolytes
     - **Target:** >500 miles range, ~$85/kWh cost
     - **Partners:** BMW, Ford, Samsung SDI, SK Innovation
     - **Status:** Pilot lines completed
     
     #### **QuantumScape** 🇺🇸
     - **Technology:** Lithium-metal anode, ceramic separator
     - **Partners:** Volkswagen (PowerCo), six automakers total
     - **Agreement:** Licensing deal for 40 GWh annual capacity (July 2024)
     
